from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Widdrington","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative from Widdrington (Northumb), recorded as  <i>Vuderintuna</i>, about 1160."],"variants":[{"name":"Wethington","meanings":["English: habitational name, a shortened form of   Wetherington  ."]},{"name":"Wetherington","meanings":["English (Northumberland and Durham): from Widdrington (Northumberland). The placename derives from an Old English personal name <i>Widuhere</i> + Old English connective <i>-ing-</i> + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."]},{"name":"Weatherington","meanings":["English (Northamptonshire): variant of   Wetherington  ."]},{"name":"Witherington","meanings":["English: either a variant of   Wetherington  , or perhaps a habitational name from Witherenden in Ticehurst (Sussex), Witherden Farm in Headcorn (Kent), or a lost place called <i>Witherington</i> or similar. The Sussex and Kent placenames probably derive from an Old English personal name <i>Wither</i> + Old English connective <i>-ing-</i> + <i>denn</i> ‘woodland pasture’."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"John de Widdrington was born about 1277, in Widdrington, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom as the son of John de Widdrington II. He married Christiana Swinburne in 1302, in Widdrington, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died before 1327, in his hometown."},"et":{"Abt 1277–Bef 1327":"umbes 1277–enne 1327","1277–1327":"1277–1327","1280–1326":"1280–1326","1275–1338":"1275–1338","1306–1372":"1306–1372","1308–1362":"1308–1362","1235–1285":"1235–1285","1275":"1275","1285":"1285","1362":"1362","1372":"1372","Abt 1306":"umbes 1306","1280":"1280","Bef 1327":"enne 1327","1338":"1338","1327":"1327","1326":"1326","1302":"1302","about 1308":"umbes 1308","1235":"1235","Abt 1277":"umbes 1277","1277":"1277","after 1285":"pärast 1285","1308":"1308","1306":"1306","England":"England","Widdrington, Northumberland, England":"Widdrington, Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Widdrington, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom":"Widdrington, Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1277–Bef 1327":"noin 1277–ennen vuotta 1327","1277–1327":"1277–1327","1280–1326":"1280–1326","1275–1